onal_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"446472\"\n  ncbi_id: \"3252\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  code: ICBN\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n','Tracheophyta E. W. Sinnott 1935: 441 [P. D. Cantino and M. J. Donoghue], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Magnolia tripetala  & Lycopodium clavatum',NULL),(2,'Pan-Tracheophyta',2,'2013-01-17 02:07:02',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,3,'P. D. Cantino and M. J. Donoghue','The definition of Pan-Tracheophyta is identical to the one we used when we first published the name (Cantino et al. 2007).   The name Polysporangiomorpha (polysporangiophytes) sensu Kenrick and Crane (1997: Table 7.2, Fig. 4.31) has an apomorphy-based definition and thus is unlikely to be fully synonymous with Pan-Tracheophyta.  Its currently known composition is the same as that of Pan-Tracheophyta, but there may have been pan-tracheophytes that preceded the evolution of multiple sporangia.  Similarly, Polysporangiophyta sensu Crane and Kenrick (1997) has the same known composition as both Pan-Tracheophyta and Polysporangiomorpha, but its name has a node-based definition and thus the clade Polysporangiophyta may be less inclusive than either of the other two.  The three names would no longer be synonyms if a fossil were to be found in the future that possesses an intermediate combination of ancestral and derived states of the three characters mentioned above as possible synapomorphies (for example, a sporophyte that is dependent on the gametophyte throughout its life, as is the case in bryophytes, but has more than one sporangium).',1,'ICBN','Cantino and Donoghue ','node-based_standard','The total clade of Tracheophyta.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Kenrick, P., and P. R. Crane\n    title: \"\"\n    publisher: Smithsonian Institution Press\n    journal: \"\"\n    book_e