II, 2003; Hilu et al., 2003; Soltis and Soltis, 2004; Burleigh et al., 2009) or Ã¢â‚¬Å“malvidsÃ¢â‚¬Â (Judd and Olmstead, 2004; Judd et al., 2008; Soltis et al., 2007; Zhu et al., 2007; APG III, 2009; Worberg et al., 2009).  However, these studies disagree on the composition of this clade.  The core groupsÃ¢â‚¬â€Brassicales, Malvales, and SapindalesÃ¢â‚¬â€are part of eurosids II (or malvids) in the context of all well-resolved phylogenies, and Huerteales are part of this clade in all studies in which representatives were included.  However, Crossosomatales, Geraniales, Myrtales, and Picramniaceae were included in eurosids II (or malvids) by some authors but not others.  In some cases, the exclusion of these taxa was due to lack of resolution (e.g., Myrtales, Geraniales and Crossosomatales in Soltis et al., 2000: Fig. 9A), absence from the study (e.g., Picramniaceae in most analyses), or the taxa being inferred not to be closely related (e.g., Geraniales in Worberg et al., 2009: Fig. 1); in other cases, the excluded taxa were inferred to be closely related to eurosids II (or malvids) but the authors applied these informal names to a smaller clade than we do here (e.g., Myrtales, Geraniales, and Crossosomatales in Burleigh et al., 2009: Fig. 3).  Our preliminary node-based definition for Malvidae (in Cantino et al., 2007) applied that name to a particular composition by including specifiers representing the four major subclades of eurosids II in Soltis et al. (2000: Fig. 9).  However, in view of the varying compositions of eurosids II and malvids, the branch-modified node-based definition adopted here seems preferable.  This definition delimits a composition identical or close to that of the clade labeled eurosids II (or malvids or Malvidae) when applied to most of the relevant phylogenies (i.e., those cited above).  For example, when applied to the phylogeny of Wang et al. (2009), Malvidae as defined here includes all of the taxa within the bracket labeled Malvidae in that paper (namely, Brassicales, Malvales, Huerteales, Sapindales, Geraniales, Myrtales, Crossosomatales, and Picramniaceae).  However, when applied to the topology of Soltis et al. (2000: Fig. 9A), the definite membership of Malvidae would be restricted to Brassicales, Malvales, Huerteales, and Sapindales (the groups included within \"eurosid II\" on that tree); the other taxa might or might not be part of Malvidae because the phylogeny (in Soltis et al., 2000) is equivocal on their placement relative to both Malvidae and Fabidae.  \n	Surprisingly, in a recent phylogenomic analysis based on numerous sequences from the nuclear genome (Lee et al., 2011, Fig. 1), the clade Malpighiales was placed within Malvidae (as sister to Brassicales), contrary to placements based largely on plastid data (which place Malpighiales in Fabidae; see Burleigh et al., 2009; Soltis et al., 2007, 2011; Wang et al., 2009).  The taxon sampling of Lee et al. (2011) was quite limited, so it is not known whether Celastrales and Oxalidales, which group with Malpighiales in most plastid-based trees, would also have been placed within Malvidae if representatives had been included.  If future phylogenetic analyses corroborate this finding of Lee et al. (2011), then application of our definition will accommodate Malpighiales (and possibly Celastrales and Oxalidales) in an expanded Malvidae.\nThe concept of this clade has been changing as the understanding of phylogeny improves, but the feature that we are trying to capture in the definition is its inclusion of everything that is closer to the original core groups of eurosids II than to the core groups of Fabidae (i.e., Fabales, Rosales, Fagales, and Cucurbitales).   When this definition is used in conjunction with our reciprocal definition of Fabidae (this volume), it ensures that Fabidae and Malvidae are always mutually exclusive (as implied by the informal names eurosids I and II), regardless of their exact composition in the context of a particular phylogeny.  This mutual exclusivity seems to us to be a more critical part of the current concept of these two clades, as represented in the highly influential APG III (2009) classification, than the inclusion or exclusion of certain subgroups (e.g., Geraniales, Myrtales, or Malpighiales), hence our preference for the definition proposed here rather than one that uses multiple internal specifiers to guarantee the inclusion of particular subgroups (other than Malvales).  However, the primary reference phylogeny (Wang et al., 2009), which is based on two nuclear genes and ten plastid genes, provides very strong support for the compositions of Fabidae and Malvidae as hypothesized here (see Composition sections for both entries).  These compositions are also strongly supported by the recent 17-gene phylogenetic analysis of angiosperms (Soltis et al., 2011).\n',1,'ICBN','W. S. Judd, D. E. Soltis, and P. S. Soltis','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The most inclusive crown clade containing Malva sylvestris L. 1753 (Malvales) but not Vicia faba L. 1753 (Fabidae).  This is a branch-modified node-based definition.  Abbreviated definition:  >âˆ‡  Malva sylvestris L. 1753 ~ Vicia faba L. 1753. ','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Wang, H.-C., M. J. Moore, P. S. Soltis, C. D. Bell, S. F. Brockington, R. Alexandre, C. C. Davis, M. Latvis, S. R. Manchester, and D. E. Soltis\n    title: Rosid radiation and the rapid rise of angiosperm-dominated forests\n    publisher: \"\"\n    journal: Proc. Nat. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.\n    book_editors: \"\"\n    series_editors: \"\"\n    figure: \"1\"\n    year: \"2009\"\n    edition: \"\"\n    volumes: \"\"\n    city: \"\"\n    volume: \"106\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 3853-3858\n    keywords: \"\"\n    abstract: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_t