al_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"8512827\"\n  ncbi_id: \"63102\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  code: ICBN\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n','Caryophyllales K. J. Perleb 1826:  [P. S. Soltis, W. S. Judd, and D. E. Soltis, 2009], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Dianthus caryophyllus  & Polygonum sachalinense  & Simmondsia chinensis  & Rhabdodendron amazonicum',NULL),(17,'Ericaceae ',2,'2013-01-17 01:10:48',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,3,'W. S. Judd and K. A. Kron','This nearly cosmopolitan clade includes about 4,100 species and was recently reviewed by Kron et al. (2002a) and Stevens et al. (2004); the former provides detailed phylogenetic analyses with extensive intra-clade sampling, employing 18S, ITS, matK, rbcL sequences, and morphology.  Although recent authors (Angiosperm Phylogeny Group, 2003; Anderberg et al., 2002; Heywood et al., 2007; Judd et al., 2008; Kron et al., 2002a; SchÃƒÂ¶nenberger et al., 2005; Stevens et al., 2004) apply the name Ericaceae in the same way it is applied here, the name has historically been applied to a non-monophyletic group originating with the same ancestor (Cronquist, 1981; Drude, 1897; Hooker, 1876; Stevens, 1971; Takhtajan, 1980), i.e., Ericaceae was formerly divided into Ericaceae sensu stricto, Epacridaceae, and Empetraceae.  In addition, the highly mycorrhizal, Ã‚Â± herbaceous (in contrast to most Ericaceae, which are woody), photosynthetic taxa frequently have been segregated as Pyrolaceae, and the non-chlorophyllous, mycoparasitic taxa have been segregated as Monotropaceae.  Sometimes the inferior-ovaried taxa have been segregated as Vacciniaceae.\n\nEnkianthus is sister to the rest of Ericaceae (Kron et al., 2002a) and differs from them in having anthers with a fibrous endothecium and opening by two longitudinal slits, monadinous pollen, and seeds with vascular bundles in the raphe (all of which are putative plesiomorphies). Anthers with an exothecium, but more or less lacking a fibrous endothecium, and seeds lacking a vascular bundle in the raphe probably are synapomorphic for the clade comprising all Ericaceae except for Enkianthus.  Pollen released in tetrahedral tetrads may also be a synapomorphy at this level, although the condition is variable within Monotropoideae, with pollen monads occurring in Orthilia, Chimaphila (some), and the mycoparasitic genera, so it may be a synapomorphy for the Arbutoideae + Ã¢â‚¬Å“early anther inversion clade.Ã¢â‚¬Â  Ã¢â‚¬Å“Pseudomonads,Ã¢â‚¬Â i.e., tetrads in which three of the four grains abort, occur in some Styphelioideae (especially Styphelieae) (Furness, 2009).  The clade comprising Vaccinioideae, Styphelioideae, Harrimanelloideae, Cassiopoideae, and Ericoideae, i.e., referred to as the Ã¢â‚¬Å“early anther inversion cladeÃ¢â‚¬Â by Kron et al. (2002a) and constituting the vast majority of the species of Ericaceae, is supported by the synapomorphy of anthers inverting early in the development of the flower.  Arbutoideae, Monotropoideae, and Enkianthus retain the plesiomorphic condition, i.e., anthers inverting just before anthesis, but the anthers of Hemitomes, Pleuricospora, and Cheilotheca (in the Monotropeae) do not invert. \n \nThe monophyly of Ericaceae is strongly supported.  See especially SchÃƒÂ¶nenberger et al., (2005), in which the clade was supported in a parsimony analysis by a bootstrap value of 98% and by a Bayesian posterior probability of 1.0, in analyses utilizing 18S and 26S nrDNA sequences, the mitochondrial genes atp1 and matR, and the chloroplast regions rbcL, atpB, ndhF, rps16, matK, trnT-F spacer, and trnV-atpE spacer.  Its monophyly has also been supported by several other phylogenetic analyses based on morphological and/or molecular characters (Anderberg, 1993; Anderberg et al., 2002; Judd and Kron, 1993; Kron, 1996; Kron and Chase, 1993; Kron et al., 2002a).  These analyses, along with those focused on relationships within the clade (Anderberg, 1994a,b; Bidartondo and Bruns, 2001; Bush and Kron, 2008; Bush et al., 2009; Crayn and Quinn, 2000; Crayn et al., 1996, 1998; Freudenstein, 1999; Goetsch et al., 2005; Hileman et al., 2001; Kron and Judd, 1997; Kron, 1997; Kron and King, 1996; Kron et al., 1999a,b, 2002b; McGuire and Kron, 2005; Oliver, 2000; Pedraza-PeÃƒÂ±alosa, 2009; Powell and Kron, 2001, 2002; Powell et al. 1996, 1997; Quinn et al., 2003; Taaffe et al., 2001; Tsukaya et al., 2008; Waselkov and Judd, 2008) have resulted in a fairly well-resolved phylogeny for the group.  Remaining problems mainly concern relationships within the Vaccinieae and among the mycoparasitic species.\n\nA node-based definition is preferred based on the well resolved phylogenetic structure within Ericaceae, especially the position of Enkianthus as sister to the remaining taxa and the monophyly of the Ã¢â‚¬Å“early anther inversion clade,Ã¢â‚¬Â\n\nThe specifier Hypopitys monotropa Crantz has long been recognized as Monotropa hypopithys L., but recent phylogenetic analyses (Bidartondo & Bruns 2001; Tsukaya et al. 2008) indicate that the genus Monotropa, as traditionally circumscribed, is non-monophyletic, and that genus is now restricted to Monotropa uniflora.\n',1,'ICBN','Jussieu ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Enkianthus campanulatus G. Nicholson 1884, Pyrola rotundifolia L. 1753, Hypopitys monotropa Crantz 1766, Arctostaphylos uva-ursi (L.) Spreng. 1825, and Erica cinerea L. 1753.  This is a node-based definition that applies to a crown clade, since all of the specifiers are extant.  Abbreviated definition: < Enkianthus campanulatus G. Nicholson 1884 & Pyrola rotundifolia L. 1753 & Hypopitys monotropa Crantz 1766 & Arctostaphylos uva-ursi (L.) Spreng. 1825 & Erica cinerea L. 1753.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Kron, K. A., W. S. Judd, P. F. Stevens,