s  Bercht. and J. Presl. 1820: 251 [W. S. Judd and K. A. Kron], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Impatiens capensis  & Erica cinerea ',NULL),(19,'Fabidae',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,3,'W. S. Judd, D. E. Soltis, and P. S. Soltis','The clade Fabidae is large and economically important, including over 51,000 species and a diversity of well-known plants such as oaks, birches, roses, figs, elms, legumes, willows, spurges, violets and squashes.  The monophyly of Fabidae has been strongly supported in several phylogenetic analyses (Burleigh et al., 2009; Soltis et al., 2007, 2011; Wang et al., 2009) and moderately supported by Soltis et al. (2000).  This clade was informally named Ã¢â‚¬Å“eurosids IÃ¢â‚¬Â in several recent phylogenetic treatments of angiosperms (Savolainen et al., 2000b; Soltis et al., 2000, 2005; Judd et al., 2002; APG II, 2003; Soltis and Soltis, 2004) and Ã¢â‚¬Å“fabidsÃ¢â‚¬Â in others (Judd and Olmstead, 2004; Judd et al., 2008; Soltis et al., 2007).  There being no previous scientific name for this clade, we (in Cantino et al. 2007) proposed and phylogenetically defined Fabidae, using a node-based definition with internal specifiers representing Celastrales, Cucurbitales, Fabales, Fagales, Huaceae, Oxalidales, Malpighiales, Rosales, and Zygophyllales.  However, we here propose a branch-modified node-based definition as a way to accommodate the varying position of Zygophyllales, which groups with Malvidae in the combined MP analysis of Wang et al. (2009: Suppl. tree 1), but is strongly supported in Fabidae in the combined ML analysis of Wang et al. (2009: Fig. 1) and in MP analyses of other data partitions in Wang et al. (2009), in agreement with several other phylogenetic analyses (e.g., Burleigh et al. 2009; Hilu et al., 2003; Savolainen et al., 2000a,b; Soltis et al., 2000, 2003, 2007, 2011).  We consider it unlikely that Zygophyllales are part of Malvidae.  The combined MP topology (in Wang et al., 2009) may be the result of long-branch attraction, because when sequences from just the slowly evolving Inverted Repeat region of the chloroplast are used, both MP and ML analyses place Zygophyllales within Fabidae (Wang et al., 2009).  Finally, we note that a recent analysis of 86 plastid genes (Moore et al., 2010) places Bulnesia (Zygophyllaceae) in Fabidae with 100% bootstrap support.\n	The positions of Myrtales, Crossosomatales, and/or Geraniales are currently unresolved relative to Fabidae and Malvidae.  In contrast to the reference phylogeny, Hilu et al. (2003) and Zhu et al. (2007) inferred the Geraniales to lie outside of both Fabidae and Malvidae, while in Soltis et al. (2007) and Zhu et al. (2007) Myrtales are placed outside of both these clades.  In addition, several of these phylogenies place some of these taxa in Fabidae (as defined here); i.e., Geraniales are so placed in the phylogeny of Worberg et al. (2009), Crossosomatales in Hilu et al. (2003), and Picramniaceae in Savolainen et al. (2000a).  The bulk of the evidence, however, suggests that these taxa are part of Malvidae rather than Fabidae.  Taxa that are part of Fabidae in nearly all recent analyses (Burleigh et al., 2009; Hilu et al., 2003; Savolainen et al., 2000a, b; Soltis et al., 2000, 2003, 2007, 2011; Wang et al., 2009 (Fig. 1; but see discussion above regarding Zygophyllales); Worberg et al., 2009; Zhu et al., 2007 (Fig. 4)) are Celastrales, Cucurbitales, Fabales, Fagales, Huaceae, Oxalidales, Malpighiales, Rosales, and Zygophyllales, except that no representatives of Huaceae were included in the analyses of Hilu et al. (2003), Soltis et al. (2011), or Worberg et al. (2009), no representatives of Fabales were included by Soltis et al. (2003), and no representatives of Zygophyllales were included by Zhu et al. (2007).  Representatives of Picramniaceae were included in only a few analyses, where they were variably inferred to belong within Fabidae (Savolainen et al., 2000a), within Malvidae (Wang et al., 2009; Soltis et al., 2011), or outside of both Fabidae and Malvidae (Savolainen et al., 2000b).  However, in a recent phylogenomic analysis based on numerous sequences from the nuclear genome (Lee et al., 2011, Fig. 1) the clade Malpighiales was placed within Malvidae (as sister to Brassicales), contrary to placements based largely on plastid data (which, as indicated above, place Malpighiales in the Fabidae). The taxon sampling of Lee et al. (2011) was quite limited, so it is not known whether Celastrales and Oxalidales, which group with Malpighiales in most plastid-based trees, would also have been placed within Malvidae if representatives had been included.  If future phylogenetic analyses corroborate this finding of Lee et al. (2011), then application of our definition will accommodate Malpighiales (and possibly Celastrales and Oxalidales) in an expanded Malvidae, and Fabidae will be correspondingly reduced in size.\n\n	The essential feature of the concept of Fabidae that we are trying to capture in the definition is its inclusion of everything that is closer to the core groups of eurosids I (i.e., Fabales, Rosales, Fagales, and Cucurbitales, which constitute the nitrogen-fixing clade; see Soltis et al., 2000, 2005; Zhu et al., 2007) than to the core groups of Malvidae (i.e., Brassicales, Malvales and Sapindales).  When this definition is used in conjunction with our reciprocal definition of Malvidae (this volume), it ensures that Fabidae and Malvidae are always mutually exclusive (as implied by the informal names eurosids I and II), regardless of their exact composition in the context of a particular phylogeny.  This mutual exclusivity seems to us to be a more critical part of the accepted concept of these two clades, as represented in the highly influential APG III (2009) classification, than the inclusion or exclusion of Zygophyllales (and possibly a few other subgroups, as noted above).  However, the primary reference phylogeny (Wang et al., 2009), which is based on two nuclear genes and ten plastid genes, provides very strong support for the compositions of Fabidae and Malvidae as hypothesized here (see Composition sections for both entries).  These compositions are also strongly supported by the recent 17-gene phylogenetic analysis of angiosperms (Soltis et al., 2011).\n',1,'ICBN','W. S. Judd, D. E. Soltis, and P. S. Soltis ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The most inclusive crown clade containing Vicia faba L. 1753 (Fabales) but not Malva sylvestris L. 1753 (Malvidae).  This is a branch-modified node-based definition.  Abbreviated definition: > Ã¯Æ’â€˜ Vicia faba L. 1753 ~ Malva sylvestris L. 1753.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Wang, H.-C., M. J. Moore, P. S. Soltis, C. D. Bell, S. F. Brockington, R. Alexandre, C. C. Davis, M. Latvis, S. R. Manchester, and D. E. Soltis\n    journal: Proc. Nat. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.\n    figure: \"1\"\n    year: \"2009\"\n    volume: \"106\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"3853\\xE2\\x80\\x933858\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Rosid radiation and the rapid rise of angiosperm-dominated forests\n  \"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Savolainen, V., M. W. Chase, S. B. Hoot, C. M. Morton, D. E. Soltis, C. Bayer, M. F. Fay, A. Y. de Bruijn, S. Sullivan, and Y.-L. Qiu\n    journal: Syst. Biol.\n    figure: 4, 5\n    year: \"2000\"\n    volume: \"49\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"306\\xE2\\x80\\x93362\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Phylogenetics of flowering plants based on combined analysis of plastid atpB and rbcL gene sequences\n  \"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"Savolai