idely used.  The corresponding informal names Ã¢â‚¬Å“monocots\" and \"monocotyledons\" have been applied to this clade in nearly all recent phylogenetic treatments of angiosperms (e.g., APG II, 2003; Chase, 2004; Judd et al., 2008; Soltis and Soltis, 2004; Soltis et al., 2005; Simpson, 2006). Our choice of Monocotyledoneae over Monocotyledones is somewhat arbitrary, but the former appears to have been used in more post-1900 classifications, floras and textbooks.  The name Monocotyledoneae was phylogenetically defined by us (in Cantino et al., 2007), using nearly the same definition as used here.  The only difference is that there was one additional specifier in the 2007 definition.  We no longer think it necessary to include Tofieldia glutinosa as a specifier because the clade Alismatales, which is already represented by another specifier, Gymnostachys anceps, is very strongly supported (Hilu et al., 2003; Chase et al., 2006; Givnish et al, 2006; Graham et al., 2006).\n',1,'ICBN','de Candolle','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Acorus calamus Linnaeus 1753, Gymnostachys anceps Robert Brown 1810 (Alismatales), and Lilium superbum Linnaeus 1762 (Liliales).  This is a node-based definition that applies to a crown clade, as all of the specifiers are extant.  Abbreviated definition: < Acorus calamus Linnaeus 1753 & Gymnostachys anceps Robert Brown 1810 & Lilium superbum Linnaeus 1762. ','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"Chase, M. W., M. F. Fay, D. S. Devey, O. Maurin, N. R\\xC3\\xB8nsted, J. Davies, Y. Pillon, G. Petersen, O. Seberg, M. N. Tamura, C. B. Asmussen, K. Hilu, T. Borsch, J. I. Davis, D. W. Stevenson, J. C. Pires, T. J. Givnish, K. J. Sytsma, M. M. McPherson, S. W. Graham, and H. S. Rai\"\n    title: \"Multigene analyses of monocot relationships: a summary. Pag