rnal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n\"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Strongylocentrotus purpuratus \"\n  specifier_authors: \"Stimpson \"\n  specifier_year: \"1857\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"594126\"\n  ncbi_id: \"7668\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Chordata  E. Haeckel  1874: (Vol. ): 22 [C.B. Cameron], converted clade name','<Petromyzon marinus  & Strongylocentrotus purpuratus ',NULL),(30,'Deuterostomia ',2,'2013-01-17 22:42:19',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,3,'C.B. Cameron','The monophyly of Deuterostomia is supported by both molecular and morphological analyses (Delsuc et al., 2006; Bourlat et al., 2006; Delsuc et al., 2008).  The name Deuterostomia has priority over Enterocoelia, and Enterocoelia has fallen from common usage. The name Neorenalia was not used until Neilsen (2001) created it as a replacement name for Deuterostomia. Neilsen (2001) expanded the taxon Deuterostomia to include not only Ambulacraria and Chordata but also Phoronida and Brachiopoda. There is no justification for applying the name Deuterostomia to the larger clade that includes the protosome taxa Phoronida and Branchiopoda. Deuterostomia has historically been applied in the way that it is defined here (Horste, 1939, Dawydoff, 1948, Hyman 1959).\n	The lack of resolution in some trees (e.g., Fig. 3 of Delsuc et al., 2008) raises the possibility that the set of taxa associated here with the name Deuterostomia (see Composition) might be paraphyletic, with the result that Deuterostomia and Bilateria could be synonyms.  In this unlikely event, Bilateria should be given precedence.',1,'ICZN','K. Grobben ','node-based_standard','The clade originating with the most recent common ancestor of Ptychodera flava Eschsch