ogical analyses (Cameron, 2005; Cameron et al. 2000; Winchell et al. 2002).  The hypothesis that the pterobranchs are the sister group of the echinoderms and the enteropneusts are the sister group of the chordates (Bateson, 1885 Nielsen, 2001) is no longer widely accepted.  Instead, hemichordates are widely regarded as monophyletic and the sister group of Echinodermata (Horst, 1939; Hyman, 1959; Dawydof, 1948; Halanych, 1996; Cameron et al., 2000).  Dawydoff (1948) created a taxon named Stomochordata to unambiguously include Enteropneusta and Pterobranchia; however, the name Hemichordata, originally applied to enteropneusts alone (Bateson, 1885), had already been applied to this group in two major works (Harmer, 1904; Horst, 1939).  Hemichordata is the name most commonly applied to the clade composed of pterobranchs and enteropneusts (e.g., Cameron et al., 2000; Winchell et al., 2002; Cannon et al., 2009) and was selected here for that reason. Deuterostomia should have precedence over Hemichordata in the context of phylogenies in which the two names are synonyms.  Members of the monotypic taxon Planctosphaeridae may be long-lived enteropneust larvae (Hadfiend and Young, 1983).',1,'ICBN','W. Bateson','node-based_standard','The least inclusive clade containing Cephalodiscus gracilis Harmer 1905 and Ptychodera flava Eschscholtz 1825.  This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to the hemichordate crown clade.  Abbreviated definition: < Cephalodiscus gracilis Harmer 1905 & Ptychodera flava Eschscholtz 1825.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Cameron, C.B., B.J. Swalla and J.R. Garey\n    title: \"Evolution of the chordate body plan: New insights from phylogenetic analysis of deuterostome phyla.\"\n    publisher: \"\"\n    book_editors: \"\"\n    figure: \"\"\n 