al disk (Cephalodiscus) (Lester, 1985), and any one colony may be dioecious or monoecious (Hyman, 1959). Atubaria, which was brought up by a deep-sea dredge off the coast of Japan, has no secreted tubes and may be a Cephalodiscus that had abandoned its tubes on collection (Dilly, 1986).  The collagenous tubes of the living Rhabdopleura have similarities to those of members of the extinct Graptolithina (Rigby, 1994), a group for which details of soft part anatomy are not known.  This apparent homology led Rickards and Durman (2006, fig. 20) to include the Graptolithina within Pterobranchia. The name Pterobranchia was selected over other names that have been applied to a group approximating this clade (see Synonyms) because it is by far the most commonly used in the classic and recent literature (e.g., Delage and HÃ©rouard, 1897; Horste, 1939; Hyman 1959; Cameron, 2005).',1,'ICZN','E. R. Lankester','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Rhabdopleura normani Allman, 1869 and Cephalodiscus dodecalophus Mâ€™Intosh, 1882 and Atubaria heterolopha Sato, 1935. This is a node-based definition in which all specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to the pterobranch crown clade. Abbreviated definition: < Rhabdopleura normani Allman 1869 & Cephalodiscus dodecalophus Mâ€™Intosh 1882 & Atubaria heterolopha Sato 1935.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Winchell, C.J., Sullivan, J., Cameron, C.B., Swalla, B.J., and Mallatt, J.\n    journal: Mol. Biol. Evol.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2002\"\n    volume: \"19\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 762-776\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"Evaluating hypothesis of deuterostome phylogeny and chordate evolution with new LSU and SSU ribosoma