rs: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Lamarck, J. B.\n    title: Histoire Naturelle des Animaux sans Vertebrates. Tome III. Tuniciers.\n    publisher: \"D\\xC3\\xA9terville\"\n    book_editors: \"\"\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1816 \"\n    edition: \"\"\n    city: Paris\n    volume: \"\"\n    pages: \"\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    abstract: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: book\n','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n\"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Ciona intestinalis \"\n  specifier_authors: \"Linnaeus \"\n  specifier_year: \"1767\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"6690344\"\n  ncbi_id: \"7719\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Tunicata  J. B. Lamarck  1816 :  [C.B. Cameron], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Ciona intestinalis ',NULL),(36,'Dalytyphloplanida ',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'T. Artois','The clade name Dalytyphloplanida was first defined by Willems et al. (2006) with a branch-based definition, using Mariplanella frisia Ax & Heller 1970 as one of two external specifiers. This species was included as an external specifier because the sister-group relationship between M. frisia and the rest of the non-kalyptorhynch rhabdocoels was supported by a jackknife value of only 81%. In the phylogeny depicted by Willems et al. (2006: Fig. 4), in which all nodes with less than 90% jackknife value are collapsed, M. frisia is part of a trichotomy with two clades: Kalyptorhynchia and a clade consisting of the rest of the non-kalyptorhynch rhabdocoels (i.e., Dalytyphloplanida). However, I think it is best not to use M. frisia as an external specifier, so that the content of the name Dalytyphloplanida is not dependent on the position of this species. If the sister-group relationship between M. frisia and the other non-kalyptorhynch rhabdocoels is corroborated, M. frisia will be part of Dalytyphloplanida. In spite of this difference in the two definitions, the clade to which Willems et al. (2006: Fig. 4) applied the name Dalytyphloplanida at least approximates the one specified by the definition used here, the only likely difference being the inclusion or exclusion of Mariplanella frisia.\nAlthough there is no clear synapomorphy for all Dalytyphloplanida, members of this clade can very easily be recognised. They all have a pharynx bulbosus, an apomorphy of Rhabdocoela, either of the rosulatus-type or of the doliiformis-type, but they lack the proboscis, the presence of which is a synapomorphy of Kalyptorhynchia (see this volume).\n',1,'ICZN','W. R. Willems et al. ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The most inclusive crown clade containing Provortex balticus (Schultze 1851) Graff 1882 but not Polycystis naegelii KÃ¶lliker 1845. This is a branch-modified node-based definition. Abbreviated definition: >â–½Provortex balticus (Schultze 1851) Graff, 1882 ~ Polycystis naegelii KÃ¶lliker 1845.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Willems, W. R., A. Wallberg, U. Jondelius, D. T. J. Littlewood, T. Backeljau, E. R. Schockaert, and T. J. Artois\n    journal: \"Zool. Scr. \"\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2006\"\n    volume: \"35\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 1-17\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"Filling a gap in the phylogeny of flatworms: relationships within the Rhabdocoela (Platyhelminthes), inferred from 18S ribosomal DNA sequences.\"\npri