fier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"7200973\"\n  ncbi_id: \"162279\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: external extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n\"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Mariplanella frisia \"\n  specifier_authors: \"Ax & Heller \"\n  specifier_year: \"1970\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"5019827\"\n  ncbi_id: \"84085\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: external extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Kalyptorhynchia  L. Graff  1905: (Vol. 83): 68-148 [T. Artois], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Polycystis naegelii  ~ Provortex balticus V Mariplanella frisia ',NULL),(38,'Rhabdocoela ',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,3,'T. Artois','The name Rhabdocoela was first introduced by Ehrenberg (1831) to denote all turbellarians with an unbranched intestinal tract. As such, the Rhabdocoela encompassed all turbellarians known at that time except for the triclads and polyclads. In 1882, Graff removed Acoela and Alloiocoela from Rhabdocoela and assigned the three resulting â€œtribiâ€ to the ordo Rhabdocoelida. In 1905, he split the Rhabdocoela further into the taxa Rhabdocoela Hysterophora and Rhabdocoela Lecithophora. The latter corresponds approximately to Rhabdocoela as we define the name here. Meixner (1938) coined the name Neorhabdocoela for a group with the same composition as the Rhabdocoela Lecithophora, and indicated the pharynx bulbosus to be a diagnostic feature for this taxon. Subsequently, the terms Rhabdocoela and Neorhabdocoela were used interchangeably, often by the same authors (e.g. Luther, 1950, 1955; Karling, 1963, 1974). Ehlers (1985) used the name Rhabdocoela for a group that included Neodermata (parasitic flatworms) as well as Meixnerâ€™s Neorhabdocoela. In later molecular phylogenies, it became clear that the Neodermata are not part of a monophyletic Rhabdocoela, and that Rhabdocoela is a very well supported clade (BaguÃ±a et al., 2001; Littlewood et al., 1999a, b; Littlewood & Olson, 2001; Lockyer et al., 2003; Joffe & Kornakova, 2001; NorÃ©n & Jondelius, 2002; Willems et al., 2006). In all these papers (and the majority of the other recent papers on this taxon), the name Rhabdocoela is used to denote the clade for which the name is defined here. That name was previously defined phylogenetically by Willems et al. (2006), who used a branch-based definition. However, because the name is being applied here to a crown clade, a node-based definition is used. \n	Of the approximately 1500 species of rhabdocoels that have been described, only a very limited number have been included in phylogenetic analyses. The most comprehensive study (Willems et al., 2006) included 56 species.\n',1,'ICZN','C. G. Ehrenberg ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Polycystis naegelii KÃ¶lliker 1845 and Provortex balticus (Schultze 1851) Graff 1882 and Mariplanella frisia Ax & Heller 1970. This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it applies to a crown clade. Abbreviated definition: <Polycystis naegelii KÃ¶lliker 1845 & Provortex balticus (Schultze 1851) Graff 1882 & Mariplanella frisia Ax & Heller 1970. ','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Littlewood, D. T. J., K. Rohde, and K. A. Clough\n    journal: Biol. J. Linn. Soc.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1999\"\n    volume: \"66\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 75-114\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"The interrelationships of all major groups of Platyhelminthes: phylogenetic evidence from morphology and molecules. \"\n  \"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"Nor\\xC3\\xA9n, M., and U. Jondelius\"\n    journal: Zool. Scr.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2002\"\n    volume: \"31\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 403-414\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"The phylogenetic position of the Prolecithophora (Rhabditophora, \\xE2\\x80\\x98Platyhelminthes\\xE2\\x80\\x99). \"\n  \"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Joffe, B.I., and E. E. Kornakova\n    title: \"Flatworm phylogeneticist: between molecular hammer and morphological anvil.\"\n    publisher: Taylor and Francis\n    book_editors: D. T. J. Littlewood, and R. A. Bray\n    series_editors: \"\"\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2001\"\n    edition: \"\"\n    volumes: \"\"\n    city: London\n    volume: \"\"\n    pages: \"\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    abstract: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: book_section\nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Willems, W. R., A. Wallberg, U. Jondelius, D. T. J. Littlewood, T. Backeljau, E. R. Schockaert, and T. J. Artois\n    journal: Zool. Scr.\n    figure: \"1\"\n    year: \"2006\"\n    volume: \"35\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 1-17\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"Filling a gap in the phylogeny of flatworms: relationships within the Rhabdocoela (Platyhelminthes), inferred from 18S ribosomal DNA sequences.\"\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n   