: \"5019827\"\n  ncbi_id: \"84085\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Rhabdocoela  C. G. Ehrenberg  1831: 1-15 [T. Artois], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Polycystis naegelii  & Provortex balticus  & Mariplanella frisia ',NULL),(40,'Schizorhynchia ',2,'2013-01-17 01:41:20',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'T. Artois','Meixner (1928) introduced the name Schizorhynchia for a taxon consisting of all kalyptorhynch flatworms with a split proboscis, and since then it has always been applied in this way (e.g. Karling, 1983; Noldt, 1989; Schilke, 1970). The monophyly of Schizorhynchia was weakly supported in earlier publications (e.g. NorÃ©n & Jondelius, 2002), but the latest published analysis on rhabdocoel flatworms, including a larger sample of species within and close to Schizorhynchia, showed very high support for its monophyly (Willems et al., 2006). The name was phylogenetically defined by Willems et al. (2006) using a branch-based definition, but to ensure that the name will always refer to the clade intended by Meixner (1928), an apomorphy-modified node-based definition is used here.\nBecause the name Schizorhynchia is based on the genus name Schizorhynchus Hallez 1894, the type of Schizorhynchus must be used as an internal specifier (PhyloCode Art. 11.7). However, both the type species (S. coecus) and the only other species of Schizorhynchus (S. tataricus Graff 1905) are known only from their original collections and therefore have not been included in any molecular analysis.  Based on their morphology, they appear to be related to the exemplars of the clade that is labeled as Schizorhynchia in the reference phylogeny.\nWhereas the proboscis is split in all schizorhynch kalyptorhynchs that have a proboscis, two species within the ectoparasite taxon Typhlorhynchus Laidlaw 1902 do not have a proboscis at all. According to Karling (1981) and Noldt (1985), Typhlorhynchus is the sister clade to Proschizorhynchus Meixner 1928 and has secondarily lost the proboscis. A thorough phylogenetic analysis based also on molecular data is needed to assess whether Typhlorhynchus is indeed part of a monophyletic Schizorhynchia.  \n',1,'ICBN','J. Meixner ','node-based_crown_clade_apomorphy-modified','The most inclusive crown clade exhibiting a proboscis split into two halves (dorsal and ventral), synapomorphic with that in Schizorhynchus coecus Hallez 1894. This is an apomorphy-modified node-based definition. Abbreviated definition: >â–½split proboscis (Schizorhynchus coecus Hallez 1894). ','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Willems, W. R., A. Wallberg, U. Jondelius, D. T. J. Littlewood, T. Backeljau, E. R. Schockaert, and T. J. Artois\n    journal: Zool. Scr.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2006\"\n    volume: \"35\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 1-17\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"Filling a gap in the phylogeny of flatworms: relationships within the Rhabdocoela (Platyhelminthes), inferred from 18S ribosomal DNA sequences.\"\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n    citation_authors: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Meixner, J.\n    journal: Zoologischer Anzeiger\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1928\"\n    volume: \"60\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 113-125\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Aberrante Kalyptorhynchia (Turbellaria Rhabdocoela) aus dem Sande der Kieler Bucht.\n','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n\"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Schizorhynchus coecus \"\n  specifier_authors: \"Hallez \"\n  specifier_year: \"1894\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"5019264\"\n  ncbi_id: \"1195801\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Schizorhynchia  J. Meixner  1928: (Vol. 60): 113-125 [T. Artois], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Schizorhynchus coecus ',NULL),(41,'Ascomycota ',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'J.W. Spatafora, M. Blackwell, & J.W. Taylor','Application of the name Ascomycota to this clade, and the choice of this name rather than the synonyms Ascomycetes and Ascomycotina, follow the phylogeny-based classification of Hibbett et al. (2007), which has been adopted in the Dictionary of the Fungi (Kirk et al., 2008) and the GenBank taxonomy (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/guide/taxonomy). In rank-based classifications (e.g., Kirk et al., 2008), the clade Ascomycota is the largest phylum of Fungi.  It is supported in molecular phylogenetic analyses (James et al., 2006; Lutzoni et al., 2004) and comprises three mutually exclusive subclades (Spatafora et al., 2006). Taphrinomycotina is sister group to a well-supported clade comprising Saccharomycotina and Pezizomycotina. Pezizomycotina includes all ascocarp-producing taxa with the exception of Neolectomycetes of Taphrinomycotina. The monophyly of Taphrinomycotina was not supported by early analyses of ribosomal data (reviewed in Sugiyama et al., 2006), but sampling of protein coding loci (RPB1, RPB2, and TEF) in multi-gene analyses provided support for its monophyly (James et al., 2006, Spatafora et al., 2006).  Saccharomycotina (Suh et al., 2006) and Pezizomycotina (Spatafora et al., 2006) are both well-supported clades (James et al., 2006, Spatafora et al., 2006).  The sister group of Ascomycota is Basidiomycota (James et al., 2006).  The fossil record of Ascomycota dates to at least the Devonian, with Paleopyrenomycites identified as part of the Rhynie Chert fossil fungi (Taylor et al., 2005), but putative ascomycete fossils have been reported from the Silurian (Sherwood-Pike & Gray, 1985).  Efforts to fit molecular phylogenies to the fossil record have estimated the origin of Ascomycota to be between 0.40 to 1.3 billion years before the present (Taylor and Berbee, 2006, Heckman et al., 2001).',1,'ICBN','H. C. Bold ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Taphrina deformans (Berk.) Tul. 1866, Saccharomyces cerevisae Meyen 1838, and Peziza vesiculosa Bull. 1790. This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant and therefore designates a crown clade.  Abbreviated definition:  < Taphrina deformans (Berk.) Tul. 1866 & Saccharomyces cerevisae Meyen 1838 & Peziza vesiculosa Bull. 1790.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"James, T. Y., F. Kauff, C. Schoch, P. B. Matheny, V. Hofstetter, C. Cox, G. Celio, C. Gueidan, E. Fraker, J. Miadlikowska, H. T. Lumbsch, A. Rauhut, V. Reeb, A. E. Arnold, A. Amtoft, J. E. Stajich, K. Hosaka, G.-H. Sung, D. Johnson, B. O\\xE2\\x80\\x99Rourke, M. Crockett, M. Binder, J. M. Curtis, J. C. Slot, Z. Wang, A. W. Wilson, A. Sch\\xC3\\xBC\\xC3\\x9Fler, J. E. Longcore, K. O\\xE2\\x80\\x99Donnell, S. Mozley-Standridge, D. Porter, P. M. Letcher, M. J. Powell, J. W. Taylor, M. M. White, G. W. Griffith, D. R. Davies, R. A. Humber, J. B. Morton, J. Sugiyama, A. Y. Rossman, J. D. Rogers, D. H. Pfister, D. Hewitt, K. Hansen, S. Hambleton, R. A. Shoemaker, J. Kohlmeyer, B. Volkmann-Kohlmeyer, R. A. Spotts, M. Serdani, P. W. Crous, K.