Ustilaginomycotina (smuts and relatives), and Agaricomycotina (mushrooms, jelly fungi, and relatives), are resolved in most analyses (Aime et al., 2006; Begerow et al., 2006; Hibbett, 2006). The positions within Basidiomycota of Entorrhizomycetes and Wallemiomycetes are controversial (Matheny et al., 2006). Entorrhizomycetes has been placed in Ustilaginomycotina (Begerow et al., 2006), but phylogenetic analyses of nuclear ribosomal RNA genes (the only molecular data available for the group) in broadly sampled datasets suggest that it is an early-diverging clade that could be the sister group of all other Basidiomycota (Matheny et al., 2006). Wallemiomycetes is also placed as an early-diverging group of Basidiomycota in analyses of nuclear ribosomal RNA genes, alone or in combination with RNA polymerase II subunits 1 and 2, and translation elongation factor 1-Î±, but analyses of the protein-coding genes without the rRNA genes suggest that Wallemiomycetes may be closely related to Agaricomycotina or Ustilaginomycotina (Matheny et al., 2006).',1,'ICBN','H. C. Bold ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Puccinia graminis Pers. 1794, Ustilago maydis (DC.) Corda 1842, Coprinus comatus (O.F. MÃ¼ll.) Pers. 1797, Entorrhiza casparyana (Magnus) Lagerh. 1888 (Entorrhizomycetidae), and Wallemia sebi (Fr.) Arx 1970. This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant and therefore designates a crown clade. Abbreviated definition: < Puccinia graminis Pers. 1794 & Ustilago maydis (DC.) Corda 1842 & Coprinopsis cinerea (Schaeff.) Redhead, Vilgalys & Moncalvo 2001 & Entorrhiza casparyana (Magnus) Lagerh. 1888 & Wallemia sebi (Fr.) Arx 1970.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"James, T. Y., F. Kauff, C. Schoch, P. B. Matheny, V. Hofstetter, C. Cox, G. Celio, C. Guei