fier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"\"\n  ncbi_id: \"4932\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n','Dikarya D. S. Hibbett, T. Y. James, and R. Vilgalys  2007: (Vol. 111): 509-547 [D. S. Hibbett, M. Blackwell, T. James, J. W. Spatafora, J. W. Taylor, and R. Vilgalys], converted clade name','>ßœCoprinopsis cinerea  & Saccharomyces cerevisiae ',NULL),(44,'Fungi ',2,'2013-01-17 01:21:06',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'D. S. Hibbett, M. Blackwell, T. James, J. W. Spatafora, J. W. Taylor, and R. Vilgalys','Application of the name Fungi to this clade, and the choice of this name rather than its synonym Eumycota, follow the phylogeny-based classification of Hibbett et al. (2007), which has been adopted in the Dictionary of the Fungi (Kirk et al., 2008) and the GenBank taxonomy (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/guide/taxonomy). The deepest branching events and the inclusion of Microsporidia (obligately intracellular parasites with highly reduced mitochondria) within Fungi are controversial. Analyses of ï¡-tubulin and ï¢-tubulin gene sequences (Keeling, 2003) suggested that the microsporidians are nested among the members of a paraphyletic grade of â€œzygomycetesâ€ (Glomeromycota, Mucoromycotina, Entomophthoromycotina, Zoopagomycotina, and Kickxellomycotina), although the precise placement was not resolved with confidence. In contrast, analyses of genes encoding 18S, 25S, and 5.8S nuclear ribosomal RNA, and two subunits of RNA polymerase II (RPB1 and RPB2) (James et al., 2006) suggested that the microsporidia are the sister group of the chytrid Rozella allomycis, and that the Microsporidia-Rozella clade is itself the sister group of all remaining Fungi. An analysis of RPB1 and 2 alone (Liu et al., 2006) also suggested that the microsporidia are the sister group of the rest of Fungi, but R. allomycis was not included in that study. Paraphyly of â€œchytridsâ€ has been inferred repeatedly and most recent analyses have also suggested that â€œzygomycetesâ€ are paraphyletic. However, the RPB1 and 2 analysis of Liu et al. (2006) suggested that the traditional zygomycetes are, in fact, monophyletic. The node-based definition of Fungi proposed here employs multiple specifiers, representing the major clades of the traditional chytrids and zygomycetes as delimited in Hibbett et al. (2007). Rozella allomycis is included as a specifier, but members of Microsporidia are not. If either of the topologies recovered by James et al. (2006) or Keeling (2003) is correct, then Microsporidia are within Fungi. In all other regards, the composition of Fungi implied by the proposed definition should be robust to rearrangements of clades within and among the traditional chytrids and zygomycetes.',1,'ICBN','A. Engler and K. Prantl ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Rozella allomycis F.K. Faust 1937, Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis Longcore, Pessier & D.K. Nichols 1999, Allomyces arbusculus E.J. Butler 1911, Neocallimastix frontalis (R.A. Braune) Vavra & Joyon ex I.B. Heath 1983, Olpidium brassicae (Woronin) P. A. Dang. 1886, Entomophthora muscae (Cohn) Fresen. 1856, Coemansia reversa Tiegh. & G. Le Monn. 1873, Piptocephalis corymbifera Vuill. 1887, Glomus intraradices N.C. Schenck & G.S. Sm. 1982, Rhizopus oryzae Went & Prins. Geerl. 1895, and Coprinopsis cinerea (Schaeff.) Redhead, Vilgalys & Moncalvo 2001. This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant and therefore designates a crown clade. Abbreviated definition: < Rozella allomycis F.K. Faust 1937 & Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis Longcore, Pessier & D.K. Nichols 1999 & Allomyces arbusculus E.J. Butler 1911 & Neocallimastix frontalis (R.A. Braune) Vavra & Joyon ex I.B. Heath 1983 & Olpidium brassicae  (Woronin) P. A. Dang. 1886 & Entomophthora muscae (Cohn) Fresen. 1856 & Coemansia reversa Tiegh