crophulariaceae in traditional classifications.  Bellini (1907) recognized the relationship among the known hemiparasitic and holoparasitic members of Scrophulariaceae and included both in his Rhinanthoideae of Scrophulariaceae.  However, Rhinanthoideae sensu Bellini differed from Orobanchaceae (as defined here) by excluding the nonparasitic Lindenbergia, as well as several hemiparasitic taxa that are now known to belong to this clade (e.g., Brandisia, Cyclocheilaceae, Nesogenes; Bremer et al., 2002; Oxelman et al., 2005; Bennett and Mathews, 2006; Morawetz et al., 2010).  In contrast, molecular studies have used the name Orobanchaceae consistently for this clade (e.g., Olmstead et al., 2001; Oxelman et al., 2005).  Young et al. (1999) provided a phylogenetic definition for Orobanchaceae that used species of Orobanche, Lindenbergia, and Schwalbea as specifiers; we include an additional specifier to emphasize the connection to Belliniâ€™s Rhinanthoideae (i.e., the hemiparasitic Castilleja linariifolia) and to accommodate phylogenetic uncertainty among molecular systematic studies (e.g., dePamphilis et al., 1997; Wolfe and dePamphilis, 1998; Young et al., 1999; Olmstead et al., 2001; Wolfe et al., 2005; Park et al., 2008; Morawetz et al., 2010).   \nPhylogenetic studies have shown that the loss of photosynthesis (i.e., holoparasitism) in this clade followed the origin of parasitism and has occurred at least five times independently, thus the group circumscribed in traditional classifications under the name Orobanchaceae or Orobanchoideae is polyphyletic (dePamphilis et al., 1997; Wolfe and dePamphilis, 1998; Young et al., 1999).  Molecular studies using plastid DNA regions (matK and rps2, Young et al., 1999; rbcL, rps2, ndhF, Olmstead et al. 2001; rps2, Park et al., 2008) support the monophyly of both a parasitic clade and a more inclusive clade within which Lindenbergia is sister to the parasitic clade.  However, support for this more inclusive clade including Lindenbergia was stronger in all studies (97% bootstrap support, Young et al., 1999; 99% bootstrap support, Olmstead et al., 2001; 86% bootstrap support, Park et al., 2008) than the support for the parasitic clade alone (92% bootstrap support, Young et al., 1999; 75% bootstrap support, Olmstead et al., 2001; 65% bootstrap support, Park et al., 2008).  Moreover, in a study of the nuclear Phytochrome A gene (Bennett and Mathews, 2006), a group of hemiparasitic taxa, including Schwalbea, forms a clade with Lindenbergia instead of with the other parasites, albeit with low bootstrap support (67%).  Likewise, relationships among the major subclades of Orobanchaceae as defined here (including both Schwalbea and Lindenbergia) received little to no bootstrap support (< 50%) using nuclear rDNA ITS sequences (Wolfe et al., 2005).  Bennett and Mathews (2006) is the only study that included both multiple species of Lindenbergia and a sampling of other taxa related to Schwalbea (e.g., Monochasma, Siphonostegia).  Considering 1) the lack of consensus among molecular systematic studies as to the relationships among the various parasitic subclades of Orobanchaceae and the non-parasitic Lindenbergia, and 2) the varying levels of statistical support for relationships among these subclades in phylogenies using plastid or nuclear DNA sequence data and widely differing taxon sampling, we are not confident that a narrow circumscription of Orobanchaceae that excludes Lindenbergia is monophyletic.  For example, such a grouping is paraphyletic if the phylogeny of Bennett and Mathews (2006) is correct.  More importantly, several putative synapomorphies including corolla organization, secondary chemistry, and stomatal regulation (Hjertson, 1995; Olmstead et al., 2001; Wolfe et al., 2005) support the inclusion of Lindenbergia in Orobanchaceae as defined here.  Of these, stomatal regulation is among the most important with respect to the parasitic nature of the large majority of the clade.  In root parasites, there is little control of parasite transpiration as water stress develops, and stomata remain open until the parasite experiences extreme water stress â€“ well beyond the level of water stress that triggers stomatal closure in non-parasitic plants (Ehleringer and Marshall, 1995).  Lindenbergia has a loss of sensitivity to water stress (Wolfe et al., 2005) similar to that measured in both hemiparasitic and holoparasitic species of Orobanchaceae (Stewart and Press, 1990; Smith and Stewart, 1990; Jiang et al., 2003; Jiang et al. 2010), whereas members of the most closely related clades do not share this loss of sensitivity (e.g., Rehmannia, Paulownia, Mimulus).  Thus, although Lindenbergia is not parasitic, it possesses a key feature associated with the evolution of parasitism.  This fact argues strongly for its inclusion in Orobanchaceae (as by Young et al., 1999; Olmstead et al., 2001; Oxelman et al., 2005; Wolfe et al., 2005; Bennett and Mathews, 2006; Park et al. 2008) and use as an internal specifier.\nAlthough, there are multiple instances in the Phytochrome A phylogeny (Bennett and Mathews, 2006) where recent gene duplications have occurred and, upon first inspection, it may seem that some taxa may not be monophyletic (e.g., Castilleja, Lathraea, Xylocalyx), we chose this as the primary reference phylogeny because, with the exception of the weakly supported position of Lindenbergia, this study largely agrees with previous phylogenetic hypotheses for the clade (e.g., Wolfe et al., 2005) and includes the most representative taxonomic sampling to date in terms of both the number of species and genera included.  \nIn their original phylogenetic definition for Orobanchaceae, Young et al. (1999) used species of Orobanche, Lindenbergia, and Schwalbea as the only specifiers.  As discussed above, the relationship between the basal subclades containing Schwalbea and Lindenbergia is not settled, and furthermore, the phylogenetic position of the holoparasitic subclade containing Orobanche is only well supported as separate from these basal subclades in the phylogenetic analysis of the Phytochrome A gene (97% bootstrap support for clade excluding the Schwalbea and Lindenbergia subclades; Bennett and Mathews, 2006).  In all of the remaining reference phylogenies, there is little resolution among the major subclades of Orobanchaceae.  Thus, in the event that Lindenbergia, Schwalbea, and Orobanche were later found to form a clade, the name Orobanchaceae (if defined with just these three specifiers, as by Young et al. [1999]) would refer to a much smaller clade than we intend or to which it has referred historically.  Therefore we include Castilleja linariifolia as an additional specifier.  Castilleja linariifolia is chosen as a specifier, even though it is not in the primary reference phylogeny, because it is the sole species of Castilleja used in several other reference phylogenies (dePamphilis et al 1997; Wolfe and dePhamphilis 1998; Young et al., 1999; Olmstead et al., 2001; Park et al., 2008).  The studies of Tank and Olmstead (2008; 2009) provide evidence that C. linariifolia is a close relative of the species of Castilleja included by Bennett and Mathews (2006).  Likewise, Orobanche major was not included in the sampling of Bennett and Mathews (2006), but is used as a specifier in accordance with the ICPN (Art. 11.7) because it is the type of Orobanchaceae in rank-based nomenclature.  It has been shown to be closely related to the species of Orobanche included in the primary reference phylogeny (Schneeweiss et al., 2004; Park et al., 2008).\n',1,'ICBN','E. P. Ventenant ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Orobanche major L. 1753, Lindenbergia philippensis (Cham. and Schltdl.) Benth. 1846, Schwalbea americana L. 1753, and Castilleja linariifolia Benth. 1846.  This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to a crown clade.  Abbreviated definition: < Orobanche major L. 1753 & Lindenbergia philippensis (Cham. and Schltdl.) Benth. 1846 & Schwalbea americana L. 1753 & Castilleja linariifolia Benth. 1846. ','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Morawetz, J. J., C. P. Randle, and A. D. Wolfe\n    journal: Taxon\n    figure: \"2\"\n    year: \"2010\"\n    volume: \"59\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 416-426\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Phylogenetic relationships within the tropical clade of Orobanchaceae.\nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Bennett, J. R. and S. Mathews.\n    journal: Am. J. Bot.\n    figure: 2, 3\n    year: \"2006\"\n    volume: \"93\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 1039-1051\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Phylogeny of the parasitic plant family Orobanchaceae inferred from phytochrome A.\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n    citation_authors: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Ventenant, E. P.\n    title: Orobanchaceae.\n    publisher: J. Drisonnier\n    book_editors: \"\"\n    series_editors: \"\"\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1799\"\n    edition: \"\"\n    volumes: \"\"\n    city: Paris\n    volume: \"2\"\n    pages: \"292\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    abstract: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: book_section\n','--- !m