ws, and R. G. Olmstead], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Orobanche major  & Lindenbergia philippensis  & Schwalbea americana  & Castilleja linariifolia ',NULL),(52,'Solanaceae',2,'2013-01-17 01:40:45',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'R. G. Olmstead','The name Solanaceae has been applied consistently to a paraphyletic group originating with the same ancestor as this clade (ranked as a family) in traditional angiosperm classifications (e. g., Cronquist, 1981; Takhtajan, 1997).  However, a series of small groups included within this clade (Duckeodendron, Nolana, Sclerophylax, Goetzeaceae), but having atypical fruit morphology, have been excluded from Solanaceae in those classifications.  \n	Molecular phylogenetic studies provide strong support for the monophyly of Solanaceae (Olmstead et al., 2000; Soltis et al., 2000; Albach et al., 2001).  Most studies identify Schizanthus as sister to the remaining taxa (Olmstead and Palmer, 1992; Olmstead and Sweere, 1994; Martins and Barkman, 2005; Olmstead et al., 2008), with a deletion (based on restriction site mapping) in the chloroplast genome providing a molecular synapomorphy for Solanaceae exclusive of Schizanthus (Olmstead and Palmer, 1992).  However, a few studies have identified Schwenckia as sister to all others (Olmstead et al., 1999; Santiago-Valentin and Olmstead, 2003), or even a clade consisting of Goetzea and Metternichia (Fay et al., 1998).  The most recent studies with the most extensive sampling and sequence data, including those with nuclear genome sequences, consistently support Schizanthus as sister to the rest of the clade (Martins and Barkman, 2005; Olmstead et al., 2008; T. Barkman, pers. comm.).  In consideration of the inconsistency of signal in some studies at the base of the tree and the relatively low support for other deep nodes, I have selected representatives of several early-diverging lineages as specifiers.\n',1,'ICBN','Jussieu','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Solanum nigrum Linnaeus 1753, Schizanthus pinnatus Ruiz et Pavon 1794, Goetzea elegans Wydler 1830, Duckeodendron cestroides Kuhlmann 1925, Schwenckia lateriflora (Vahl) Carvalho (originally described as Chaetochilus lateriflorus Vahl) 1969, Salpiglossis sinuata Ruiz et Pavon 1794, Benthamiella skottsbergii Soriano, and Petunia axillaris (Lam.) Britton, Stearns, and Poggenb. 1888.  This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to a crown clade.  Abbreviated definition: < Solanum nigrum Linnaeus 1753 & Schizanthus pinnatus Ruiz et Pavon 1794 & Goetzea elegans Wydler 1830 & Duckeodendron cestroides Kuhlmann 1925 & Schwenckia lateriflora (Vahl) Carvalho 1969 & Salpiglossis sinuata Ruiz et Pavon 1794 & Benthamiella skottsbergii Soriano & Petunia axillaris (Lam.) Britton, Stearns, et Poggenb. 1888.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Olmstead, R.G. and J.D. Palmer\n    journal: Ann. Mo. Bot. Gard.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1992\"\n    volume: \"79\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 346-360\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"A chloroplast DNA phylogeny of the Solanaceae:  subfamilial relationships and character evolution. \"\n  \"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Fay, M. F., R. G. Olmstead, J. E. Richardson, E. Santiago, G. T. Prance, and M. W.  Chase\n    journal: Kew Bull.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1998\"\n    volume: \"53\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 203-212\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Molecular data support the inclusion of Duckeodendron cestroides in Solanaceae.\n  \"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAcc