fier_name: \"Alisma plantago-aquatica \"\n  specifier_authors: L.\n  specifier_year: \"1753 \"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"\"\n  ncbi_id: \"\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: external extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n','Petrosaviidae S. W. Graham and W. S. Judd 2007: (Vol. 56): 822â€“846 [S. W. Graham, W. S. Judd and W. J. D. Iles], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Lilium candidum  & Petrosavia stellaris  ~ Acorus calamus V Alisma plantago-aquatica ',NULL),(59,'Poineae ',2,'2013-01-17 01:46:26',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,2,'J.M. Saarela and S.W. Graham','The clade here named Poineae was first inferred in a combined analysis of morphological and rbcL data by Linder and Kellogg (1995), and later by Michelangeli et al. (2003) in an analysis of monocot phylogeny based on morphology and two genes. The clade has generally been inferred with strong support in large-scale molecular studies that have sampled different combinations of genes and taxa in Poales and relatives (i.e., Bremer 2002; Chase et al., 2006; Givnish et al, 2010; Graham et al., 2006; Saarela and Graham, 2010), although a weakly conflicting relationship was recovered in some analyses in Davis et al. (2004). While the composition of the clade seems clear, inferences about relationships among its components vary, including the identity of the sister group of the grasses, and the affinities of Flagellariaceae and Centrolepidaceae (e.g., above references; Doyle et al., 1992; Katayama and Ogihara, 1996; Briggs et al., 2000; Linder et al., 2000; Davis et al., 2004, 2006; Linder and Rudall, 2005; Marchant and Briggs, 2007; Briggs et al., 2010).\nMultiple names, both formal and informal, have been applied to the clade here named Poineae. Poales was used widely for this clade in morphological and early molecular-based classifications (e.g., Dahlgren, 1980; Dahlgren and Clifford, 1982; Dahlgren et al. 1985; Campbell and Kellogg, 1987; Linder, 1987; Kellogg and Linder, 1995; Kubitzki, 1998), whereas the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group circumscribed Poales more broadly (APG, 1998; APG II, 2003; APG III, 2009). The clade Poineae has since been referred to as â€œcore Poalesâ€ or â€œPoales s.s.â€ (e.g., Michelangeli et al., 2003; Ramos et al., 2005; Marchant and Briggs, 2007), though some authors have construed â€œcore Poalesâ€ more broadly (e.g., Linder and Rudall, 2005) or narrowly (e.g., Leitch et al., 2010). The informal names â€œgraminidsâ€ and â€œgraminoidsâ€ are widely used, particularly in the non-scientific literature, to refer to grasses and grass-like plants, including sedges and rushes, which are not included in Poineae. However, â€œgraminoid cladeâ€ (e.g., Bremer, 2002; Trethewey et al., 2005), â€œgraminoid Poalesâ€ (Marchant and Briggs, 2007) and â€œgraminidsâ€ (e.g., Chase, 2004) have been used for Poineae. â€œGraminidsâ€ has also been used for a less inclusive clade comprising Ecdeiocoleaceae, Flagellariaceae, Joinvilleaceae and Poaceae, with the clade comprising Anarthriaceae, Centrolepidaceae and Restionaceae referred to as â€œrestiidsâ€, and Poineae referred to as the â€œgraminid-restiid cladeâ€ (Linder and Rudall, 2005; Rudall et al., 2005; Givnish et al. 2010).\nThe name Poineae was used by Thorne (1968, 1992) in his earlier classifications for a suborder that included only Poaceae. Shipunov (2003) used Poineae for a group with nearly the same composition as Poineae here but including the distantly related Dasypogonaceae; he later removed Dasypogonaceae from Poineae (Shipunov, 2007, 2010). Poineae is designated here as a new clade name because it has not been validated (i.e., with a description or diagnosis, or with reference to one that is validly published) under the ICBN (McNeill et al., 2006; see Reveal, 2010), and thus does not qualify as a preexisting name under the PhyloCode.',0,'ICBN','','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Poa pratensis Linnaeus 1753 (Poaceae), Flagellaria indica Linnaeus 1753 (Flagellariaceae), and Restio paludosus Pillans 1922 (Restionaceae). This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to a crown clade. Abbreviated definition: < Poa pratensis L. 1753 & Flagellaria indica Linnaeus 1753 & Restio paludosus Pillans 1922.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Bouchenak-Khelladi, Y., N. Salamin, V. Savolainen, F. Forest, M. van der Bank, M.W. Chase, and T. R. Hodkinson\n    journal: Mol. Phylogenet. Evol.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2008\"\n    volume: \"47\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"488\\xE2\\x80\\x93505\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: \"Large multi-gene phylogenetic trees of the grasses (Poaceae): Progress towards complete tribal and generic level sampling.\"\nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Bremer, K.\n    journal: Evolution\n    figure: \"1\"\n    year: \"\"\n    volume: \"56\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"1374\\xE2\\x80\\x931387\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Gondwanan evolution of the grass alliance of families (Poales).\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n    citation_authors: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\n','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n\"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Poa pratensis \"\n  specifier_authors: Linnaeus\n  specifier_year: \"1753\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"465984\"\n  ncbi_id: \"4545\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n\"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Flagellaria indica \"\n  specifier_authors: Linnaeus\n  specifier_year: \"1753\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"1853450\"\n  ncbi_id: \"13529\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n\"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Restio paludosus \"\n  specifier_authors: Pillans\n  specifier_year: \"1922\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"8379538\"\n  ncbi_id: \"178419\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n','Poineae  J.M. Saarela and S.W. Graham , new clade name','>âˆ‡Poa pratensis  & Flagellaria indica  & Restio paludosus ',NULL),(60,'Leguminosae',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'M. J. Sanderson, M. F. Wojciechowski, M. M. McMahon and M. Lavin 2007','Leguminosae is a large clade of great economic and ecological importance, which traditionally comprises three major subgroups.  Caesalpinioids and mimosoids are mostly tropical/subtropical trees and shrubs; papilionoids are tropical, subtropical and temperate plants of extremely diverse habit. Concentrated among papilionoids are also some of the most economically important crops on the planet, used for food (peas, beans, soybeans, lentils, peanuts, etc.), forage (alfalfa, clovers, vetches, etc.) and many other purposes. Perhaps owing in part to their ability to fix atmospheric nitrogen via symbiotic interactions with rhizobial bacteria in their specialized root nodules, legumes can be found in most vegetation types and are especially successful on nutrient poor soils (Lewis et al., 2005).\n\nDespite the highly stable content of Leguminosae, arguments about rank have dogged its taxonomic history and led to acceptance of the names Leguminosae, Fabaceae, Leguminales, and Fabales in various works. Especially problematic is the ambiguous use of Fabaceae for both the clade here named Leguminosae and the subclade of Leguminosae comprising the papilionoid legumes only (e.g., Fabaceae sensu Cronquist, 1981). Recent treatments (e.g. Lewis et al., 2005) tend to recognize a single family Leguminosae, equivalent to our usage. Lewis and Schrire (2003) discussed the arguments over the choice of Fabaceae or Leguminosae, both of which are acceptable under the ICBN. In addition, we note that the suffix â€œ-osaeâ€ has no rank-dependent meaning in classical botanical nomenclature, which seems to tip the balance in favor of Leguminosae for phylogenetic nomenclature.\n\nThe monophyly of Leguminosae is unambiguously supported by all molecular phylogenetic analyses (see those cited above under Reference Phylogeny). We supplemented these works with a new (unpubl.) analysis of a larger sample of plastid matK sequences for legume outgroups than has been combined in one analysis previously (i.e., either Hilu et al., 2003 or Wojciechowski et al., 2004), including representatives of Connaraceae, Sapindaceae, Crossosomataceae, and Zygophyllaceae, many of which have been discussed in older literature as putative outgroups (Dickison, 1981). None were more closely related to Leguminosae than the three outgroup specifiers used in the definition. Evidence from several molecular markers now points to Polygalaceae (950 spp.), Surianaceae (8 spp.) and Quillaja (4 spp.) as the closest relatives. Molecular phylogenies sampling multiple representatives of Polygalaceae and Surianaceae (Forest et al., 2007) support each of these taxa as monophyletic, thus allowing us to use a single exemplar of each as an external specifier to exclude them from the crown clade designated by our definition.\n\nMost recent phylogenetic analyses place representatives of a paraphyletic Caesalpinioideae spanning the earliest nodes in the Leguminosae, with its tribe Cercideae, or tribes Cercideae plus Deterieae, comprising the sister group of all other legumes (Wojciechowski et al., 2004; Forest et al., 2007). Thus, we considered using a node-based definition like \"the least inclusive clade containing Cercis canadensis and Vicia faba,\" which is supported by these recent studies. However, Bruneau et al. (2001), using a larger taxon sample of caesalpinioids than these other studies, reported a sensitivity of the basal sister group relationships to outgroup selection. We therefore hesitate to use this node-based definition, although we would not be surprised if it were to become feasible in the future.\n\nAlthough we do not define it formally here, the name Apo-Leguminosae may ultimately prove useful for the clade stemming from the ancestor in which the legume fruit originated. The earliest unambiguous fossil Leguminosae are from the Paleocene, but typically these have been assigned to subclades of the crown group Leguminosae as defined herein (Herendeen and Dilcher, 1992). Only fossils possessing legumes but indisputably residing outside the crown group would require reference to Apo-Leguminosae.',1,'ICBN','Jussieu','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The clade originating with the most recent common ancestor of Vicia faba Linnaeus 1753 and all extant organisms or species that share a more recent common ancestor with Vicia faba than with Polygala californica Nuttall 1840, Quillaja saponaria Molina 1782, or Suriana maritima Linnaeus 1753. This is a branch-modified node-based definition and designates a crown clade. Abbreviated definition: >ïƒ‘ Vicia faba Linnaeus 1753 ~ Polygala californica Nuttall 1840 âˆ¨ Quillaja saponaria Molina 1782 âˆ¨ Suriana maritima Linnaeus 1753.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Morgan, D. R., D. E. Soltis, and K. R. Robertson\n    journal: Am. J. Bot.\n    figure: \"1\"\n    year: \"1994\"\n    volume: \"81\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 890-903\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Systematic and evolutionary implications of rbcLsequence variation in Rosaceae.\n  \"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Soltis, D. E., P. S. Soltis, M. W. Chase, M. E. Mort, D. C. Albach, M. Zanis, V. Savolainen, W. H. Hahn, S. B. Hoot, M. F. Fay, M. Axtell, S. M. Swensen, L. M. Prince, W. J. Kress, K. C. Nixon, and J. S. Farris\n    journal: Bot. J. Linn. Soc.\n    figure: 7-8\n    year: \"2000\"\n    volume: \"133\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 381-461\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: Angiosperm phylogeny inferred from 18S rDNA, rbcL, and atpB sequences.\n  \"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Kajita, T., H. Ohashi, Y. Tateishi, C. Bailey, and J. Doyle\n    journal: Syst. Bot.\n    figure: 1-3\n    year: \"2001\"\n    volume: \"26\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 515-536\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n    title: RbcL and legume phylogeny, with particular reference to Phaseoleae, Millettieae, and allies.\n  \"3\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Hilu, K. W., T. Bor