itutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"456312\"\n  ncbi_id: \"32256\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n','Leguminosae Jussieu 1789: 345 [M. J. Sanderson, M. F. Wojciechowski, M. M. McMahon and M. Lavin 2007], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Vicia faba  & Polygala californica  & Quillaja saponaria  & Suriana maritima ',NULL),(61,'Alveolata ',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'A.G.B. Simpson, B.S. Leander, and M. Dunthorn','A close phylogenetic relationship between three major groups of microbial eukaryotesâ€”ciliates (Ciliophora), dinoflagellates (Dinoflagellata) and apicomplexan parasites (Apicomplexa, e.g. Plasmodium, Toxoplasma)â€”was initially identified primarily through analyses of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) gene sequences (Gadahjar et al., 1991; Wolters, 1991; Taylor, 1999).  Almost all relevant phylogenetic reconstructions since have supported this basic relationship (van de Peer and de Wachter, 1997; Fast et al. 2002; Leander and Keeling, 2004; RodrÃ­guez-Ezpeleta et al. 2007; Burki et al. 2007; Yoon et al., 2008).  Molecular phylogenetic analyses indicate strongly that Apicomplexa and Dinoflagellata are more closely related to each other than to Ciliophora (van de Peer and de Wachter, 1997; Fast et al., 2002; Burki et al. 2007).\nAdditional, more obscure, members of Alveolata include the predatory or parasitic Perkinsidae, Colpodellida and Ellobiopsidae, all of which share morphological similarities to Apicomplexa and/or Dinoflagellata and are related to them in molecular phylogenies (Simpson and Patterson, 1996; Siddall et al., 1997; van de Peer and de Wachter, 1997; NorÃ©n et al., 1999; Saldarriaga et al., 2003; Leander et al., 2003; Silberman et al., 2004), and Chromera and Vitrella, photosynthetic organisms related in nuclear gene phylogenies to Colpodellida and Apicomplexa (Moore et al. 2008, ObornÃ­k et al., 2012).  Colponema (a predatory cell) and Acrocoelus (a parasite) are poorly known organisms with possible cortical alveoli (Mignot and Brugerolle, 1975, Fernandez et al., 1999) that are often assigned tentatively to Alveolata, pending molecular data (Cavalier-Smith, 1998; Patterson, 1999; Cavalier-Smith and Chao, 2003; Leander and Keeling, 2003).  In the past Alveolata has occasionally been proposed to include some other groups that are now assigned elsewhere; e.g.; Hemimastigophora, Haplosporidia and Kathablepharis (Cavalier-Smith, 1998; Leander and Keeling, 2003).\n	The name Alveolata was first used by Cavalier-Smith (1991), who used it to refer to what he considered at the time to be a paraphyletic group containing Apicomplexa, Ciliophora and â€˜Dinozoaâ€™ (i.e. Dinoflagellata, and little-studied dinoflagellate-like organisms).  Although Cavalier-Smith (1991) cited another manuscript for the introduction of the taxon Alveolata, the other manuscript was not actually published.  Cavalier-Smith (1993) later did provide an explicit diagnosis of Alveolata, and later still explicitly considered the taxon to represent a monophyletic group (Cavalier-Smith, 1998).  The name Alveolata has been widely adopted and is now consistently used to refer to a clade containing Apicomplexa, Ciliophora, and Dinoflagellata (e.g. Cavalier-Smith, 2002; Leander and Keeling, 2003; Adl et al., 2005).  The only names we are aware of that are used for this clade are Alveolata and the related informal name â€˜alveolatesâ€™ (e.g. Patterson and Sogin, 1992; Patterson, 1999; Baldauf, 2003; Simpson and Roger, 2004).',1,'ICZN','T. Cavalier-Smith ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The least inclusive clade containing Alexandrium tamarense (Lebour 1925) Balech 1992 (Dinoflagellata), Tetrahymena thermophila Nanney & McCoy 1976 (Ciliophora), and Toxoplasma gondii (Nicolle & Manceaux 1908) Nicolle & Manceaux 1909 (Apicomplexa).  This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to a crown clade.  Abbreviated definition: < Alexandrium tamarense (Lebour 1925) Balech 1992 & Tetrahymena thermophila Nanney & McCoy 1976 & Toxoplasma gondii (Nicolle & Manceaux 1908) Nicolle & Manceaux 1909.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"Silberman J. D., A. G. Collins, L. A. Gershwin, P. J. Johnson and A. J. Roger. 2004. \"\n    journal: J. Eukaryot. Microbiol.\n    title: Ellobiopsids of the genus Thalassomyces are alveolates.\n    figure: \"3\"\n    year: \"2004\"\n    volume: \"51\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 246-252\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n  \"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"Moore, R. B., M. Oborn\\xC3\\xADk, J. Janou\\xC5\\xA1kovec, T. Chrudimsk\\xC3\\xBD, M. Vancov\\xC3\\xA1, D. H. Green, S. W. Wright, N. W. Davies, C. J. S. Bolch and K. Heimann, J. Slapeta, O. Hoegh-Guldberg, J. M. Logsdon, Jr. and D. A. Carter\"\n    journal: \"Nature \"\n    title: A photosynthetic alveolate closely related to apicomplexan parasites.\n    figure: 2C\n    year: \"2008\"\n    volume: \"451\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 959-963\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: \"van de Peer, Y. and R. de Wachter. 1997. \"\n    journal: J. Mol. Evol.\n    title: Evolutionary relationships among the eukaryotic crown taxa taking into account site-to-site rate variation in 18S rRNA.\n    figure: 2, 4\n    year: \"1997\"\n    volume: \"45\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: 619-630\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n    citation_authors: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Cavalier-Smith, T.\n    title: Cell diversification in heterotrophic flagellates.\n    publisher: Clarendon Press\n    book_editors: D. J. Patterson, and J. Larsen\n    series_editors: \"\"\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"1991\"\n    edition: \"\"\n    volumes: \"\"\n    city: Oxford, U.K.\n    volume: \"45\"\n    pages: 113-131\n    keywords: \"\"\n    abstract: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: book_section\n','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n\"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: Alexandrium tamarense\n  specifier_authors: \"(Lebour 1925) Balech \"\n  specifier_year: \"1992\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"7178000\"\n  ncbi_id: \"2926\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n\"1\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Tetrahymena thermophila \"\n  specifier_authors: \"Nanney & McCoy \"\n  specifier_year: \"1976\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"5433016\"\n  ncbi_id: \"312017\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n\"2\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Toxoplasma gondii \"\n  specifier_authors: \"(Nicolle & Manceaux 1908) Nicolle & Manceaux \"\n  specifier_year: \"1909\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"6755246\"\n  ncbi_id: \"1080348\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Alveolata  T. Cavalier-Smith  1991: (Vol. 45): 113-131 [A.G.B. Simpson, B.S. Leander, and M. Dunthorn], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Alexandrium tamarense & Tetrahymena thermophila  & Toxoplasma gondii ',NULL),(62,'Archaeplastida',2,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'A.G.B. Simpson','The evolutionary history of eukaryotic cells is complicated by the phenomenon of â€˜endosymbiosisâ€™, whereby a cell, hereafter referred to as the nucleocytoplasmic host, acquired as an internal resident a second organism â€“ the endosymbiont, and over evolutionary time this endosymbiont was reduced to the status of a highly integrated organelle (albeit one that still carries a small genome in almost all cases).  In a literal sense, all crown eukaryotes are evolutionary chimeras between the nucleocytoplasmic host and the endosymbiont that became the mitochondrion.  Photosynthetic eukaryotes, however, are doubly chimeric because their plastids are derived, ultimately, from endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.  In the case of plastid-bearing eukaryotes, â€˜primary endosymbiosisâ€™ refers to the situation where the plastid descended directly from an endosymbiosis established between a cyanobacterium and a eukaryotic host cell.  The resulting organelle is called a â€˜primary plastidâ€™ and has two bounding membranes.  This is distinct from the more complicated phenomena of â€˜secondary endosymbiosisâ€™ and â€˜tertiary endosymbiosisâ€™, in which the plastid descended directly from an endosymbiosis involving a eukaryotic endosymbiont that had itself inherited the organelle as a consequence of an earlier primary endosymbiosis.  The resulting â€˜secondary plastidsâ€™ (or â€˜tertiary plastidsâ€™) generally have three or four bounding membranes (Keeling, 2004, Gould et al., 2008).\nThree major clades of extant eukaryotes have plastids of primary endosymbiotic origin: Viridiplantae (synonyms Viridaeplantae, Chloroplastida, Chlorobionta; includes Embryophyta and the â€˜green algaeâ€™), Rhodoplantae (â€˜red algaeâ€™) and Glaucophyta (also known as Glaucocystophyta).  Phylogenetic analyses of plastid-encoded genes (e.g. Turner et al., 1999; Rodriguez-Ezpeleta et al. 2005) and the presence of unique gene order organizations on plastid genomes indicate that plastids are a clade, relative to extant cyanobacteria (see McFadden, 2001; Palmer, 2003).  These data suggest that there was a single primary endosymbiosis, presumably in a common ancestor of Viridiplantae, Rhodoplantae and Glaucophyta.  An alternative explanation holds that there were multiple primary endosymbioses involving closely related prokaryote endosymbionts but (potentially) distantly related eukaryote hosts.  This second model drew support from the fact that Viridiplantae and Rhodoplantae and/or Glaucophyta did not form a clade in many phylogenies of one or a few nucleus-encoded genes (e.g. Stiller and Hall, 1997).  Recently, however, phylogenies based on datasets of large numbers of nucleus-encoded proteins have usually indicated that the nucleocytoplasmic host components of Viridiplantae, Rhodoplantae and Glaucophyta are closely related to one another (RodrÃ­guez-Ezpeleta et al., 2005, 2007; Hackett et al. 2007; Burki et al., 2008, 2012, see Inagaki et al., 2009), consistent with the hypothesis of a single primary endosymbiotic event in their common ancestor.  Further, the single primary endosymbiosis hypothesis is strongly supported by the shared presence of apparently derived components of the plastid protein import machinery in Viridaeplantae and Rhodoplantae (see Palmer, 2003; McFadden and van Dooren, 2004) and Glaucophyta (Price et al. 2012).  This complete system presumably had to have evolved after the establishment of the endosymbiotic association, since its function is to import proteins encoded by the host nucleus.  This dates the last common ancestor of the plastids of Viridiplantae, Rhodoplantae and Glaucophyta to after the establishment of the endosymbiosis, and not before.\nViridiplantae, Rhodoplantae and Glaucophyta have been referred to collectively as the Kingdom Plantae.  This usage dates back at least as far as one of several alternative schemes proposed by Cavalier-Smith (1981), although he did not at the time consider plastids to be an apomorphy for Plantae (see Cavalier-Smith, 1981, p. 476-477).  Subsequently â€˜Plantaeâ€™ or â€˜plantsâ€™ has been equated with the primary plastid-bearing eukaryotes by some, especially protistologists (e.g. Cavalier-Smith, 1998; Baldauf et al., 2000; Simpson et al., 2004; Keeling et al., 2005; RodrÃ­guez-Ezpeleta et al., 2005; Hackett et al., 2007; Burki et al., 2008).  However, it is much more common, especially among botanists, to associate the name Plantae with much less inclusive clades (e.g. Raven et al., 2005).  This is due in part to the historical popularity of the Margulis version of the â€˜five kingdomâ€™ classification scheme for life, in which Kingdom Plantae is an approximate synonym of Embryophyta (Margulis, 1971).  Of course, under earlier â€˜two kingdomâ€™ systems of life, Plantae was an extremely broad and heterogenous grouping that included all photosynthetic organisms (as well as fungi), and it remains very common to use the term â€˜plantsâ€™ as a non-taxonomic term for photosynthetic organisms in general (e.g. Judd et al., 2007, chapter 7).\nTo avoid the confusion associated with Plantae, a new name, Archaeplastida was coined as an outside-of-code taxon name by Adl et al. (2005) to refer to the clade of primary plastid-containing algae.  A different name, Primoplantae, was introduced independently by Palmer et al. (2004).  Of the two, Archaeplastida is used far more commonly in the scientific literature, and thus is used here as the name for this clade.\n	As yet there is not a clear resolution of the precise phylogenetic position of Archaeplastida relative to other major clades of eukaryotes (e.g. RodrÃ­guez-Ezpeleta et al. 2007; Burki et al., 2007, 2008), therefore it is difficult to nominate clear apomorphies for Archaeplastida, other than the presence of primary plastids (which is all-but-unique to this clade amongst extant eukaryotes; see Marin et al., 2005 for an exception), and genic features associated with the plastid.  Other distinctive (i.e. rare across other eukaryotes), but not unique features include the use of starches as primary carbohydrate stores, and flattened mitochondrial cristae (Cavalier-Smith, 1998).\nThe qualifying clause in the definition addresses two different phylogenetic scenarios:  1) In my view the name Archaeplastida should be inapplicable if Viridiplantae and Rhodoplantae were found to derive from separate events of primary endosymbiosis.  The first part of the qualifying clause (necessary inclusion of Galdieria sulphuraria) is intended to ensure this.  2) The inference of monophyly of the Archaeplastida nucleocytoplasmic component (see above) has been made largely on the basis of unrooted trees, thus strictly speaking, Archaeplastida forms a clan (sensu Wilkinson et al., 2007) in these analyses, rather than a clade.  The second part of the qualifying clause (necessary exclusion of Homo sapiens) is intended make the name Archaeplastida inapplicable should the root of a clade consisting of most or all extant eukaryotes fall â€˜withinâ€™ Archaeplastida.  By contrast, in my view it would be appropriate to retain the name Archaeplastida should one or more small clades without primary plastids prove to lie within the clade identified by the apomorphy of a primary plastid. Cryptophyta for example shows close phylogenetic affinity with Archaeplastida (e.g. Burki et al., 2012) and the possibility that this taxon may branch within Archaeplastida cannot be excluded at present.  Thus I have not specified a more stringent qualifying clause.\n',1,'ICBN','S. M. Adl et al.','node-based_crown_clade_apomorphy-modified','The most inclusive crown clade consisting of organisms that contain plastids that are synapomorphic with those in Arabidopsis thaliana (Linnaeus) Heynhold 1842, provided that it includes Galdieria sulphuraria (Galdieri) Merola in Merola et al. 1981 (Rhodoplantae) and excludes Homo sapiens Linnaeus 1758.  In this definition, \"plastids\" refers to the organelles also known as chloroplasts in the broadest sense, that is, all homologous organelles irrespective of appearance or function; \"synapomorphic\" means stemming directly from the same event of primary endosymbiosis and does not include later origin through a subsequent event of secondary endosymbiosis (see Comments).  This is an apomorphy-modified node-based definition with a qualifying clause.  Abbreviated definition: >ïƒ‘ Plastids derived through primary endosymbiosis (Arabidopsis thaliana (Linnaeus) Heynhold 1842).  Qualifying clause: The name does not apply to any clade that does not include Galdieria sulphuraria (Galdieri) Merola in Merola et al. 1981 or that does include Homo sapiens Linnaeus 1758.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Burki, F., K. Shalchian-Tabrizi and J. Pawlowski\n    journal: \"Biol. Lett. \"\n    title: \"Phylogenomics reveals a new \\xE2\\x80\\x98megagroup\\xE2\\x80\\x99 including most photosynthetic eukaryotes.\"\n    figure: \"1\"\n    year: \"2008\"\n    volume: \"4\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"366\\xE2\\x80\\x93369\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n    citation_authors: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Adl, S. M. and 27 others\n    journal: J. Eukaryot. Microbiol.\n    title: The new higher level classification of eukaryotes with emphasis on the taxonomy of protists.\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"2005\"\n    volume: \"52\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"399\\xE2\\x80\\x93451\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n\"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: Arabidopsis thaliana\n  specifier_authors: (Linnaeus) Heynhold\n  specifier_year: \"1842\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"451511\"\n  ncbi_id: \"3702\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICBN\n','Archaeplastida S. M. Adl et al. 2005: (Vol. 52): 399â€“451 [A.G.B. Simpson], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Arabidopsis thaliana',NULL),(63,'Eukarya',2,'2013-01-17 01:08:34',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'A.G.B. Simpson','The distinction between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells is often considered to be the most fundamental discontinuity in the living world (Stanier et al., 1963).  There are many profound differences between eukaryotic and prokaryotic cells (see diagnostic apomorphies).  Of these, the presence of a membrane-bounded nucleus in eukaryotes is generally seen as the defining feature of these cells.  Compartmentalization by membranes of the chromosomal material is extremely rare and phylogenetically restricted in prokaryotes, and is almost certainly analogous, not homologous, to the eukaryote nucleus (Fuerst, 2005).\nAcknowledgment of the distinction between what we now refer to as prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells was apparent during the 19th century and common by the 1930â€™s (see Copeland, 1938, 1956; Stanier, 1970; Sapp 2005), and by the 1960s most major structural differences had been documented (see Stanier and van Niel, 1962; Allsopp, 1969; Stanier, 1970).  Phylogenies estimated from ribosomal RNA genes and many â€˜universalâ€™ protein-coding genes typically infer an extremely long (and well-supported) branch separating prokaryotic and eukaryotic organisms (e.g. Sogin, 1991; Ciccarelli et al., 2006; Foster et al., 2009).  Providing the root of the tree does not lie among eukaryotes, the monophyly of eukaryotes is not seriously doubted.  In practice, there has been a widespread, though not universal, belief that eukaryotes are, in fact, a monophyletic group descended from prokaryotic ancestors.  The chief reasons, historically, for this view have been forms of â€˜simple-is-primitiveâ€™ arguments, but the universal presence of mitochondrial organelles, which are derived from Proteobacteria, indicates strongly that the eukaryote crown clade at least is derived (and monophyletic).   It is also widely held that strong evidence of prokaryotic life extends earlier into the geological record than reliable evidence of eukaryotic life, consistent with eukaryotes being derived (LÃ³pez-GarcÃ­a et al., 2006).  The use of universal paralog pairs to root the tree of life usually places the root of the tree among prokaryotes, but is likely unreliable, or at least difficult to interpret (see Philippe and Forterre, 1999, Zhaxybayeva et al., 2005).  Fusion hypotheses for the origin of eukaryotic cells (there are several â€“ see Embley and Martin, 2006) generally also imply that eukaryotes are derived with respect to prokaryotic cells and monophyletic.\nThe term â€˜eucaryotesâ€™ was introduced by Chatton (1925), along with â€˜procaryotesâ€™.  He perhaps intended the term to refer only to unicellular forms, not to â€˜higherâ€™ animals or plants or macroalgae (Chatton, 1925, p. 76), and the occasional uses of the term for the next two to three decades were apparently mostly in this sense (Katscher, 2004).  However, the term â€˜eucaryotesâ€™ soon came to be associated unequivocally with all nucleated organisms (e.g. Chadefaud, 1960), and it is in this sense that the term â€˜eucaryoticâ€™ was widely disseminated by Stanier and colleagues (Stanier and van Niel, 1962; Stanier et al., 1963; see Katscher, 2004; Sapp 2005).  Starting around 1960, various taxon names were introduced that were based on the word â€˜eucaryoteâ€™ and implicitly or explicitly included multicellular as well as unicellular eukaryotes: Eukaryonta was introduced and defined by Fott (1959), while Eucaryota was used by Christensen (1962), and Traub (1964) introduced and defined Eucaryotae.  Stebbins (1964) used Eukaryota in passing.  A few workers assigned ranks to these taxa, usually considering them â€˜superkingdomsâ€™ or â€˜kingdomsâ€™.  By the end of the 1960s, Allsopp (1969) noted that eukaryotic cells were widely known as â€˜Eucaryotaâ€™.  The alternate transliteration â€˜Eukaryotaâ€™ has now become more popular in works in English.  â€˜Eukaryotesâ€™ has also overwhelmingly supplanted â€˜eucaryotesâ€™ in English works (e.g. compare Stanier and van Niel, 1962 and Stanier, 1970).  Using a different linguistic root, Jeffrey (1971) proposed the name Eucytota for eukaryotic organisms, but this has never been widely used.\nMuch later, Woese, Kandler and Wheelis (Woese et al., 1990) proposed the taxon Eucarya for all eukaryotic cells, assigning it the new rank of â€˜Domainâ€™.  It was not made clear why they proposed a new name, rather than using one of the several similar names already in existence.  Nonetheless, the name has become rapidly and widely adopted, though with a â€˜kâ€™ instead of â€˜câ€™ in a large majority of cases, consistent with the now-dominant informal term â€˜eukaryoteâ€™. \nAlthough the name Eukaryota is seemingly dominant in general literature, the name Eukarya is used much more frequently than Eukaryota in scientific literature (with other near-homonyms, e.g., Eukaryotae and Eukaryonta, being little used).  It is therefore proposed that Eukarya be adopted as the name of this clade, to comply with Phylocode recommendation 10.1A.  I do not know who was the first to use Eukarya as a taxon name, rather than Woese et al.â€™s (1990) original Eucarya.  It was probably introduced by several groups in parallel, in most or all cases unwittingly.  To comply with PhyloCode article 17.5 and recommendation. 9.8A, the authors of the preexisting name are considered here to be Creti et al. (1991); this is the first published use found that was not an obvious and isolated error.  The definition given here follows the recommendation (Rec. 10.1B) that widely used names be attached to crown clades.\n',1,'ICZN','Creti et al.','node-based_crown_clade_apomorphy-modified','The most inclusive crown clade exhibiting a nucleus, bounded by a nuclear envelope and pierced by nuclear pores, synapomorphic with those in (most cells of) Homo sapiens Linnaeus 1758. This is an apomorphy-modified node-based definition that is intended to refer to a crown clade.  Abbreviated definition: >âˆ‡ Nucleus (Homo sapiens Linnaeus 1758).','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Foster, P. G., C. J. Cox and T. M. Embley\n    journal: Phil. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B. Biol. Sci.\n    title: \"The primary divisions of life: a phylogenomic approach employing composition-heterogeneous methods.\"\n    figure: 2, 4\n    year: \"2009\"\n    volume: \"364\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"2197\\xE2\\x80\\x932207\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\nprimary-phylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Ciccarelli, F. D., T. Doerks, C. von Mering, C. J. Creevey, B. Snel and P. Bork\n    journal: Science\n    title: Toward automatic reconstruction of a highly resolved tree of life.\n    figure: \"2\"\n    year: \"2006\"\n    volume: \"311\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"1283\\xE2\\x80\\x931287\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\ndescription: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_type: book\n    citation_authors: \" \"\n    title: \" \"\npreexisting: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Creti, R., F. Citarella, O. Tiboni, A. Sanangelantoni, P. Palm and P. Cammarano\n    journal: J Mol Evo\n    title: \"Nucleotide sequence of a DNA region comprising the gene for elongation  factor l\\xEF\\x81\\xA1 (EF-l\\xEF\\x81\\xA1) from the ultrathermophilic archaeote Pyrococcus woesei: phylogenetic implications.\"\n    figure: \"\"\n    year: \"\"\n    volume: \"33\"\n    number: \"\"\n    pages: \"332\\xE2\\x80\\x93342\"\n    keywords: \"\"\n    isbn: \"\"\n    url: \"\"\n    doi: \"\"\n    treebase_tree_id: \"\"\n    citation_type: journal\n','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n\"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  specifier_name: \"Homo sapiens \"\n  specifier_authors: \"Linnaeus \"\n  specifier_year: \"1758\"\n  specifier_collector: \"\"\n  spcecifier_collector_number: \"\"\n  specifier_institutional_code: \"\"\n  ubio_id: \"109086\"\n  ncbi_id: \"63221\"\n  treebase_id: \"\"\n  file: \"\"\n  specifier_type: species\n  specifier_kind: internal extant\n  specifier_kind_type: specifier\n  specifier_code: ICZN\n','Eukarya Creti et al. (Vol. 33): 332â€“342 [A.G.B. Simpson], converted clade name','>âˆ‡Homo sapiens ',NULL),(64,'Opisthokonta',2,'2013-01-17 01:55:20',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,1,'A.G.B. Simpson and M. Medina','Animals and fungi were treated as separate kingdoms under the pedagogically popular â€˜five kingdomâ€™ systems of life derived from Whittaker (1969).  Cavalier-Smith (1987), however, proposed that fungi were closely related to animals and to the unicellular/colonial choanoflagellates.  (A relationship between animals, or at least sponges, and choanoflagellates had been proposed earlier, owing to morphological similarities between choanoflagellates and sponge choanocytes â€“ James-Clark, 1868; see King, 2004.)  Among the reasons for suspecting a relationship between fungi, animals and choanoflagellates was the distinctive shared combination of flattened but not discoidal mitochondrial cristae, and a single posterior flagellum in motile flagellated cells (Cavalier-Smith, 1987).  A few years afterwards, some ribosomal RNA gene phylogenies supported this close relationship (e.g. Wainwright et al, 1993), while analyses of several protein-coding genes inferred an animal-fungus clade in the absence of data from choanoflagellates and also revealed a shared 12-amino-acid insertion in translation elongation factor 1Î± proteins (Baldauf and Palmer, 1993).  Many subsequent molecular phylogenetic analyses employing large samples of genes and/or taxa have confirmed a close relationship between animals, choanoflagellates and fungi (e.g. Lang et al., 2002; Medina et al. 2003; Philippe et al., 2004; RodrÃ­guez-Ezpeleta et al., 2007) but have also demonstrated that certain other unicellular eukaryotes of previously obscure affinities also fall with or within this clade.  These include: the diverse, parasitic Ichthyosporea (approximate synonyms Mesomycetozoea or â€˜DRIPâ€™s â€“ see Ragan et al., 1996; Mendoza et al., 2002), the filose amoeba group Nucleariidae (Amaral Zettler et al., 2001), the unusual and poorly known slime mold Fonticula (Brown et al., 2009), the small, sometimes flagellated Ministeria (Cavalier-Smith & Chao, 2003), and the small amoeboid parasites Corallochytrium (Cavalier-Smith & Allsopp, 1996) and Capsaspora (see Ruiz-Trillo et al., 2004).  Recent molecular phylogenies of multiple proteins divide the grouping into two well supported subclades:  i) Metazoa, Choanoflagellata and Ichthyosporea plus, where studied, Corallochytrium, Ministeria and Capsaspora, and ii) Fungi and, where studied, Nucleariidae and Fonticula (Lang et al., 2002; Steenkamp et al., 2006; Ruiz-Trillo et al., 2006, 2008; Shalchian-Tabrizi et al., 2008; Brown et al., 2009; Liu et al., 2009; Wegener Parfrey et al. 2010).  The first subclade has been referred to as Holozoa (Lang et al., 2002), the second subclade as Holomycota (Liu et al., 2009), Nucletmycea (Brown et al., 2009), and, possibly in error, â€˜Holofungiâ€™ (Lara et al. 2010).  Where studied, all of these organisms have, at most, one emergent flagellum (see Cavalier-Smith & Chao, 2003; Mendoza et al. 2002), and the characteristic â€˜animal-fungalâ€™ EF1A insertion (Steenkamp et al., 2006).  Recent studies based on comparison of whole genomes have uncovered other molecular characters apparently restricted to animals and fungi (and, where studied, choanoflagellates), for example novel genes or shared lateral gene transfers (see Elias, 2008). \n	Opisthokonta was apparently first proposed by Copeland (1956) as a new high-level taxon for the â€˜chytrid fungiâ€™ (sensu lato), which are the only true fungi to have a flagellated stage.  Copeland included within his phylum Opisthokonta one class, the previously created taxon Archimyces, which he identified by the same characters as the phylum (i.e. the phylum was a redundant taxon).  Opisthokonta is not now used to refer to chytrids, and current molecular phylogenies suggest that â€˜chytridsâ€™ sensu lato are paraphyletic (e.g. James et al., 2006). \nThe name â€˜Opisthokontaâ€™ was subsequently introduced independently by Cavalier-Smith (1987; legend for figure 23.2) for a very different concept â€”a hypothesized clade of animals, fungi and choanoflagellates.  Because of this independence and the large differences in concept, Opisthokonta sensu Copeland (1956) and sensu Cavalier-Smith (1987) are regarded here as homonyms.  Despite the capitalization, the name was not proposed as a formal taxon by Cavalier-Smith (1987) â€”he considered choanoflagellates to be members of a paraphyletic kingdom Protozoa, whilst animals and fungi each had their own kingdoms.  Nevertheless, the names â€˜Opisthokontaâ€™ and â€˜opisthokontsâ€™ are now widely accepted as referring to the animal-fungal-choanoflagellate clade (e.g. Cavalier-Smith & Chao, 1995; Baldauf et al., 2000; Baldauf, 2003; Simpson & Roger, 2004; Adl et al., 2005; Keeling et al., 2005; Wegener Parfrey et al. 2006; Steenkamp et al., 2006).  Opisthokonta was treated as an out-of-code, rankless taxon by Adl et al., (2005), who circumscribed it with reference to the posterior flagellum and flat cristae (following Cavalier-Smith, 1987).  There are no formal synonyms in common use.  Notwithstanding Copelandâ€™s (1956) earlier homonym (which is dormant, has synonyms, and does not readily refer to a clade â€“ see above), we have selected Opisthokonta Cavalier-Smith (1987) for the animal-fungal-choanoflagellate clade, which preserves the contemporary usage of this name.\nThe stipulation in the definition that Opisthokonta not include Dictyostelium discoideum (Amoebozoa) or Arabidopsis thaliana (Archaeplastida) is intended to prevent the name from being applied in the (highly unlikely) case that the clade proves to include one or more of the major groups of well-known eukaryotes that have always been excluded from Opisthokonta, including the case where the root of the eukaryotic tree falls among the opisthokonts.  Non-application of the name in the latter case would be consistent with our 