 both molecular and morphological analyses (Cameron, 2005; Mallatt and Winchell, 2007).  Xenoturbellida (not included in the reference phylogeny) is sister taxon to Ambulacraria (Bourlat et al., 2006).  Ambulacraria might be defined in such a way as to include Xenoturbellida, but Xenoturbellida lacks ambulacra and wasnâ€™t discovered until 1949, long after the name Ambulacraria was coined.  For these reasons Xenoturbella is not included as an internal specifier. The clade name Ambulacraria was selected over its synonyms both because it has priority and because it is the most commonly used.  Should Tunicata, Cephalochordata or Vertebrata be found to be part of Ambulacraria, in which case Ambulacraria would become synonymous with Deuterostomia (as defined in this volume), Deuterostomia should have precedence over Ambulacraria.',1,'ICZN','V. E. Metschnikoff ','node-based_crown_clade_branch-modified','The clade originating with the most recent common ancestor of the hemichordates Cephalodiscus gracilis Harmer 1905, Saccoglossus pusillus Ritter 1902, and Ptychodera flava Eschscholtz 1825, and the echinoderms Florometra serratissima A. H. Clark 1907, Asterias amurensis Lutken 1871, Arbacia punctulata Lamarck 1816, and Cucumeria salva Lampert 1885.  This is a node-based definition in which all of the specifiers are extant; it is intended to apply to the ambulacrarian crown clade.  Abbreviated definition: < Cephalodiscus gracilis Harmer 1905 & Saccoglossus pusillus Ritter 1902 & Ptychodera flava Eschscholtz 1825 & Florometra serratissima A. H. Clark 1907 & Asterias amurensis Lutken 1871 & Arbacia punctulata Lamarck 1816 & Cucumeria salva Lampert 1885.','--- !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \nphylogeny: !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n  \"0\": !map:ActiveSupport::HashWithIndifferentAccess \n    citation_authors: Winchell, C.J., J. Sullivan, C.B. Cameron, B.J. Swalla, and J. Mallatt\n    journal: Mol. Biol. Evol.\n    title: Evaluating hypothesis 